<subSubSection pageId="0" pageNumber="239" type="diagnosis">
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="239">Diagnosis.</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="239">
The morphology of the genitalia of 
<taxonomicName class="Insecta" genus="E." kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="E. copaquillaensis" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="0" pageNumber="239" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="copaquillaensis">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="239">E. copaquillaensis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
sp. nov. (Figs 
<figureCitation captionStart="Figures 3–6" captionStartId="F3" captionText="Figures 3 - 6. Genitalia of Eupithecia copaquillaensis sp. nov. 3. Male genitalia in ventral view, phallus removed; 4. Phallus in lateral view; 5. Smaller cornutus; 6. Female genitalia in ventral view. Scale bar: 0.4 mm." figureDoi="10.3897/nl.44.73247.figures3-6" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/602328" pageId="0" pageNumber="239">3-6</figureCitation>
) closely resembles that of 
<taxonomicName class="Insecta" genus="E." kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="E. atacama" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="0" pageNumber="239" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="atacama">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="239">E. atacama</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
(Vojnits, 1985) (Figs 
<figureCitation captionStart="Figures 8–11" captionStartId="F5" captionText="Figures 8 - 11. Genitalia of Eupithecia atacama (Vojnits, 1985). 8. Male genitalia in ventral view, phallus removed; 9. Phallus in lateral view; 10. Smaller cornutus; 11. Female genitalia in ventral view. Scale bar: 0.4 mm." figureDoi="10.3897/nl.44.73247.figures8-11" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/602330" pageId="0" pageNumber="239">8-11</figureCitation>
), with type locality near Freirina village in the Huasco Province of northern Chile, also recorded in a few localities of the Coquimbo Province (
<bibRefCitation author="Vojnits, AM" journalOrPublisher="Acta Zoologica Hungarica" pageId="0" pageNumber="239" pagination="405 - 418" refId="B25" refString="Vojnits, AM, 1985. New South American genera and species of Eupithecini (Lepidoptera: Geometridae). Acta Zoologica Hungarica 31: 405 - 418" title="New South American genera and species of Eupithecini (Lepidoptera: Geometridae)." volume="31" year="1985">Vojnits 1985</bibRefCitation>
). 
<taxonomicName class="Insecta" genus="E." kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="E. atacama" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="0" pageNumber="239" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="atacama">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="239">E. atacama</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
was originally described in 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Vojnits" authorityYear="1985" class="Insecta" family="Geometridae" genus="Heteropithecia" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Heteropithecia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="0" pageNumber="239" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="239">Heteropithecia</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
Vojnits, 1985, a monotypic genus synonymized with 
<taxonomicName class="Insecta" family="Geometridae" genus="Eupithecia" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Eupithecia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="0" pageNumber="239" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="239">Eupithecia</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
by 
<bibRefCitation author="Rindge, FH" journalOrPublisher="Bulletin of the American Museum of Natural History" pageId="0" pageNumber="239" pagination="269 - 363" refId="B16" refString="Rindge, FH, 1987. The Eupithecia of Chile (Lepidoptera, Geometridae). Bulletin of the American Museum of Natural History 186: 269 - 363" title="The Eupithecia of Chile (Lepidoptera, Geometridae)." volume="186" year="1987">Rindge (1987)</bibRefCitation>
. This synonymy has been followed in subsequent studies (
<bibRefCitation author="Rindge, FH" journalOrPublisher="American Museum Novitates" pageId="0" pageNumber="239" pagination="1 - 14" refId="B17" refString="Rindge, FH, 1991. The Eupithecia of Chile (Lepidoptera, Geometridae) II. American Museum Novitates 3020: 1 - 14" title="The Eupithecia of Chile (Lepidoptera, Geometridae) II." volume="3020" year="1991">Rindge 1991</bibRefCitation>
; 
<bibRefCitation DOI="https://doi.org/10.1071/9780643101050" author="Parsons, MS" journalOrPublisher="Nota Lepidopterologica" pageId="0" pageNumber="239" refId="B14" refString="Parsons, MS, Scoble, MJ, Honey, MR, Pitkin, LM, Pitkin, BR, 1999. The Catalogue. In: Scoble MJ (Ed.) Geometrid Moths of the World: a Catalogue (Lepidoptera: Geometridae) (2 volumes). CSIRO Publishing, Collingwood, [xxv,] 1016 pp. https://doi.org/10.1071/9780643101050" title="The Catalogue. In: Scoble MJ (Ed.) Geometrid Moths of the World: a Catalogue (Lepidoptera: Geometridae) (2 volumes). CSIRO Publishing, Collingwood, [xxv,] 1016 pp." url="https://doi.org/10.1071/9780643101050" year="1999">Parsons et al. 1999</bibRefCitation>
), including the redefinition of 
<taxonomicName class="Insecta" family="Geometridae" genus="Eupithecia" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Eupithecia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="0" pageNumber="239" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="239">Eupithecia</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
by 
<bibRefCitation DOI="https://doi.org/10.11646/zootaxa.3587.1.2" author="Mironov, VG" journalOrPublisher="Zootaxa" pageId="0" pageNumber="239" pagination="46 - 64" refId="B9" refString="Mironov, VG, Galsworthy, AC, 2012. A generic level review of Eupithecia Curtis and some closely related genera based on the Palaearctic, Nearctic and Oriental fauna (Lepidoptera, Geometridae, Larentiinae). Zootaxa 3587: 46 - 64, DOI: https://doi.org/10.11646/zootaxa.3587.1.2" title="A generic level review of Eupithecia Curtis and some closely related genera based on the Palaearctic, Nearctic and Oriental fauna (Lepidoptera, Geometridae, Larentiinae)." url="https://doi.org/10.11646/zootaxa.3587.1.2" volume="3587" year="2012">Mironov and Galsworthy (2012)</bibRefCitation>
. The males of 
<taxonomicName class="Insecta" genus="E." kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="E. copaquillaensis" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="0" pageNumber="239" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="copaquillaensis">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="239">E. copaquillaensis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
sp. nov. and 
<taxonomicName class="Insecta" genus="E." kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="E. atacama" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="0" pageNumber="239" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="atacama">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="239">E. atacama</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
have two cornuti on the vesica, the larger of which is a narrow horseshoe-like piece with asymmetrical arms. However, the smaller cornutus is sub-cylindrical and curved on the distal half in 
<taxonomicName class="Insecta" genus="E." kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="E. copaquillaensis" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="0" pageNumber="239" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="copaquillaensis">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="239">E. copaquillaensis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
sp. nov., while it is depressed, squat and concave in 
<taxonomicName class="Insecta" genus="E." kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="E. atacama" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="0" pageNumber="239" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="atacama">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="239">E. atacama</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
. The females of the two species have a mainly membranous corpus bursae with small teeth-like signa. However, the signa are grouped in a dense semicircular patch in 
<taxonomicName class="Insecta" genus="E." kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="E. copaquillaensis" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="0" pageNumber="239" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="copaquillaensis">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="239">E. copaquillaensis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
sp. nov., while those of 
<taxonomicName class="Insecta" genus="E." kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="E. atacamae" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="0" pageNumber="239" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="atacamae">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="239">E. atacamae</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
are arranged in longitudinal stripes.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="0" pageNumber="239" type="description">
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="239">Description.</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="239">
<emphasis bold="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="239">
Male (Fig. 
<figureCitation captionStart="Figure 1" captionStartId="F1" captionText="Figure 1. Male paratype of Eupithecia copaquillaensis sp. nov. in dorsal view. Scale bar: 5 mm." figureDoi="10.3897/nl.44.73247.figure1" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/602326" pageId="0" pageNumber="239">1</figureCitation>
).
</emphasis>
Forewing length 9.9-10.1 mm.
</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="239">
<emphasis bold="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="239">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="239">Head</emphasis>
.
</emphasis>
Frons and vertex creamy white with brownish gray scattered scales. Labial palp concolorous with frons and vertex. Antenna filiform, creamy white dorsally, ciliated ventrally, cilia longer than flagellomere diameter.
</paragraph>
<caption doi="10.3897/nl.44.73247.figure1" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/602326" pageId="0" pageNumber="239" start="Figure 1" startId="F1">
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="239">
<emphasis bold="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="239">Figure 1.</emphasis>
Male paratype of 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Vargas" authorityYear="2021" class="Insecta" family="Geometridae" genus="Eupithecia" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Eupithecia copaquillaensis" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="0" pageNumber="239" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="copaquillaensis">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="239">Eupithecia copaquillaensis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
sp. nov. in dorsal view. Scale bar: 5 mm.
</paragraph>
</caption>
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="239">
<emphasis bold="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="239">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="239">Thorax</emphasis>
.
</emphasis>
Mainly creamy white with brownish gray and yellowish brown scattered scales. Foreleg mainly brownish gray with creamy white scattered scales. Mid- and hindleg mainly creamy white with brownish gray scattered scales; tibial spurs creamy white. Forewing mainly creamy white with abundant brownish gray and a few yellowish brown scattered scales; poorly differentiated brownish gray transverse stripes broader and darker near costal margin, narrower and lighter towards posterior margin. Hindwing mainly creamy white with poorly differentiated brownish gray transverse stripes near posterior wing margin and brownish gray scattered scales on distal half.
</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="239">
<emphasis bold="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="239">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="239">Abdomen</emphasis>
.
</emphasis>
Mainly creamy white with brownish gray and yellowish brown scattered scales. Tergum VIII (Fig. 
<figureCitation captionStart="Figure 2" captionStartId="F2" captionText="Figure 2. Male abdominal segment VIII of Eupithecia copaquillaensis sp. nov. Sternum (left) in ventral view; tergum (right) in dorsal view. Scale bar: 0.2 mm." figureDoi="10.3897/nl.44.73247.figure2" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/602327" pageId="0" pageNumber="239">2</figureCitation>
) square-like; anterior margin straight, distinctly sclerotized, shortly projected laterally; posterior margin with short semicircular projection in the middle. Tergum VIII (Fig. 
<figureCitation captionStart="Figure 2" captionStartId="F2" captionText="Figure 2. Male abdominal segment VIII of Eupithecia copaquillaensis sp. nov. Sternum (left) in ventral view; tergum (right) in dorsal view. Scale bar: 0.2 mm." figureDoi="10.3897/nl.44.73247.figure2" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/602327" pageId="0" pageNumber="239">2</figureCitation>
) as two separate longitudinal rods depressed anteriorly, medially curved posteriorly.
</paragraph>
<caption doi="10.3897/nl.44.73247.figure2" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/602327" pageId="0" pageNumber="239" start="Figure 2" startId="F2">
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="239">
<emphasis bold="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="239">Figure 2.</emphasis>
Male abdominal segment VIII of 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Vargas" authorityYear="2021" class="Insecta" family="Geometridae" genus="Eupithecia" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Eupithecia copaquillaensis" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="0" pageNumber="239" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="copaquillaensis">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="239">Eupithecia copaquillaensis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
sp. nov. Sternum (left) in ventral view; tergum (right) in dorsal view. Scale bar: 0.2 mm.
</paragraph>
</caption>
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="239">
<emphasis bold="true" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="239">Male genitalia</emphasis>
(Figs 
<figureCitation captionStart="Figures 3–6" captionStartId="F3" captionText="Figures 3 - 6. Genitalia of Eupithecia copaquillaensis sp. nov. 3. Male genitalia in ventral view, phallus removed; 4. Phallus in lateral view; 5. Smaller cornutus; 6. Female genitalia in ventral view. Scale bar: 0.4 mm." figureDoi="10.3897/nl.44.73247.figures3-6" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/602328" pageId="0" pageNumber="239">3-5</figureCitation>
). Uncus broad, depressed basally, narrow, spine-like distally, with pointed apex. Tegumen narrow, left and right parts completely separated. Saccus broadened ventrally, posterior margin broadly rounded. Juxta as a transverse ellipsoid stripe, calcar broadly U-shaped. Transtilla as a transverse stripe. Labides with anterior arm medially curved, bearing an apical finger-like papilla with short setae on distal half; posterior arm straight, bearing a semicircular slightly sclerotized papilla. Valva elongated, broader basally, narrowing distally, apex rounded, costal sclerotized band not reaching apex, sacculus slightly sclerotized. Phallus sub-cylindrical, anterior apex rounded, broadening distally; vesica with two cornuti, larger cornutus a narrow horseshoe-like piece with asymmetrical arms, smaller cornutus a sub-cylindrical piece curved on distal half.
</paragraph>
<caption doi="10.3897/nl.44.73247.figures3-6" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/602328" pageId="0" pageNumber="239" start="Figures 3–6" startId="F3">
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="239">
<emphasis bold="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="239">Figures 3-6.</emphasis>
Genitalia of 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Vargas" authorityYear="2021" class="Insecta" family="Geometridae" genus="Eupithecia" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Eupithecia copaquillaensis" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="0" pageNumber="239" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="copaquillaensis">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="239">Eupithecia copaquillaensis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
sp. nov. 
<emphasis bold="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="239">3.</emphasis>
Male genitalia in ventral view, phallus removed; 
<emphasis bold="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="239">4.</emphasis>
Phallus in lateral view; 
<emphasis bold="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="239">5.</emphasis>
Smaller cornutus; 
<emphasis bold="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="239">6.</emphasis>
Female genitalia in ventral view. Scale bar: 0.4 mm.
</paragraph>
</caption>
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="239">
<emphasis bold="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="239">Female.</emphasis>
Forewing length similar to male. Antenna with cilia shorter than flagellomere diameter. Wings slightly lighter than those of male, with less brownish gray and more yellowish brown scales.
</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="239">
<emphasis bold="true" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="239">Female genitalia</emphasis>
(Fig. 
<figureCitation captionStart="Figures 3–6" captionStartId="F3" captionText="Figures 3 - 6. Genitalia of Eupithecia copaquillaensis sp. nov. 3. Male genitalia in ventral view, phallus removed; 4. Phallus in lateral view; 5. Smaller cornutus; 6. Female genitalia in ventral view. Scale bar: 0.4 mm." figureDoi="10.3897/nl.44.73247.figures3-6" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/602328" pageId="0" pageNumber="239">6</figureCitation>
). Papilla analis lobe-like, slightly sclerotized near anterior margin, with hair-like setae. Posterior apophysis narrow, rod-shaped, about twice the length of papilla analis. Anterior apophysis narrow, rod-shaped, about half the length of papilla analis; ventral arm about same length as papilla analis, distally depressed and slightly broadened. Antrum broad, membranous. Ductus bursae short, membranous. Corpus bursae mainly membranous, with longitudinal striations, small teeth-like signa grouped in a dense semicircular patch. Ductus seminalis at apex of a narrow, finger-like appendix bursae near the base of corpus bursae.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="0" pageNumber="239" type="etymology">
